at you from another room.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;They ring pretty clearly now, confused, but not disoriented.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Your chest feels better too. You can take most of a breath without feeling like you’ve been hit by a tractor-trailer. You even manage to avoid yelping when you find the upper limit.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Maybe nanobots aren’t so bad, though you like the way ET does it better.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’re still on the couch, which you now realize isn’t quite long enough to accommodate you. You must have kicked the Symbiote off at some point, because it’s sitting in a rumpled pile on the floor. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The symbiote, or Kali’s blanket or whatever, is old and worn-looking, like her shirt. A variety of images and insignias scatter the fabric, each stitched earnest, well-meaning needlework. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A few of the icons you recognize as spacecraft, but most of them are lost to you. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It reminds you a little of the NASA sheets you had when you were nine.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Alien symbiote, huh?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Turns out confirmation bias is a hell of a drug. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;In less comfy, optimistic news, the blanket on the floor means your fucked up leg is exposed. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;That becomes the first item on your “things I’d really rather not look at” list, and you set right to avoiding it.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It turns out you’d actually judged the room pretty well during your previous brush with consciousness, which is funny because now it seems more like a dream than anything else. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1"> &gt;It’s maybe a little bigger than a motorhome cabin, and, while it looks like it was once rather sharp, is now furnished somewhat haphazardly. The decor is mostly neat, but gives you the impression that someone gave up about two-thirds of the way through cleaning it. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A metallic desk sits adjacent to the couch, its surface cluttered and finish dulled beneath a layer of dust.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The table in front of you is scattered with notebooks, an electronic tablet, and a few print documents. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;One of the latter is rather conspicuously a copy of Popular Science from 1991, and is open to a page about the Space Shuttle.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;In the far corner sits a pair of chairs, both built with broad gaps at their bases which you presume are for tail-routing. They face inward as if around a TV, but close as you can tell there’s nothing there.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;In the near corner, a pile of what looks to be clothing has built up probably a bit taller than originally intended. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The place certainly seems lived in, which you suppose makes perfect sense.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Wander the galaxy for a while probing random creatures, and eventually you quit being so tidey.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Like moving away to college, you figure.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Only somehow it hadn’t been what you were expecting at all.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Frankly, when you guessed the room was cluttered, you figured it was cluttered with, you don’t know, SINISTER things.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’re rather happy to have been wrong.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="d