omething original and insightful, to go on the plaques commemorating First Contact.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Something not sperging about nanobots, like that whole One Small Step thing.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;If you don’t live to see Earth again, you could at least sound cool dying.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’ll have to give that some thought, but knowing you, it can’t be TOO MUCH thought.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’ll start heading that way and see what comes to you. You’ll come up with something, right?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You duck back out into the corridor and start the opposite way, the deck  jostling a little beneath you in the thermals rising from the desert floor.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Okay, so what are your options?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Quote someone else. Maybe track 1 again. That would be modest and easy.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But nobody would remember YOU for it. If you’re honest with yourself, you do kind of like the idea of having something with your name on it.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You should probably still say whatever you’re going to say “on behalf of the people of Earth” though, so that’s somewhere to start.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;On behalf of the people of Earth..., you are, uh, honored to make her acquaintance. May our, or may we or something, find knowledge and--. No, you should say peace first. People like peace. ...may we find peace and knowledge in a common understanding--. No, no, too wordy. ...peace and knowledge in each other’s company as we turn to face the Universe together. Yeah. That’ll do. You can do this. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You plaster your hair down again and stop before what you’re pretty sure is the door to the flight deck. You straighten your shirt once more, and look up at the ceiling.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Hey, Niv?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “That’s a storage closet, anon. Next door.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;God damnit. At least it’s another second to prepare. You take a breath and steel yourself for the moment.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Niv?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “That’s it. I’ll get the lock.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The flight deck is smaller than you were expecting, and dense. The panel is broad and set forward under a set of bulkily-framed windows. It’s split down the middle by a center console that looks more complicated than the geopolitical situation in the Middle East, and crowned by an overhead so cluttered it’s not worth even trying to comprehend. Notes in various forms plaster the room like wallpaper. You’re pretty sure at least half of them are important.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Kal’Rashe seems perfectly at home in all of it though.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She’s fiddling very deliberately with a pair of dials on the overhead, tail wrapped around behind her and the black tips of her ears reaching just high enough to crest the back of the captain’s chair. For a second you don’t think she notices you, then something she’s watching satisfies her, and she spins to face you.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Anon!”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A look of wonder spreads across her face and makes her whiskers stiffen. Her half-smirk starts, but falters. She glances to Nivia, who’s occupying the right seat for what you suppose are symbolic purposes.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Your controls, Niv?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “I’ve got the vessel,” the hologram chirps</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Nivia gives you a look suggesting she’s wishing you luck, then evaporates. The controls go on manipulating themselves.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Kal’Rashe rises to greet you, you swear looking a little taller than she used to. Must be the ears, you figure, though it doesn’t help that she looks to have bathed and dressed herself up a bit for the occasion.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She’s wearing a sleek, gray jacket that looks like someone tried to make dinner-wear out of a lab coat by replacing the buttons and adding a chrome insignia to the lapel. Her collar hangs open by a few notches, revealing the folds of a black bandana bundled underneath. A few constellations are stitched into its fabric with strands of thread as white as her fur, which looks quite a bit softer than it used to. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The outfit, while it strikes you a bit odd, is tight in the right places. You do your absolute best not to think about that too much. It also manages to strike you a little intimidating, but the uncertainty in her face makes up for some of that. There’s something hopeful about it. Almost childishly hopeful, like a kid who’s writing a letter to Santa. She approaches you slowly, grasping at one of her paws with the other.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “You’re really one of them,” she whispers, eyes bright and curious in the amber glow of the cockpit illumination, “It’s an honor.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Shit, that wasn’t what she was supposed to say. If she couldn’t have been something more foreign and less, uh, distracting, the least she could have done was stick to the imaginary script you had in your head for how the meeting of your species was supposed to go down. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Your mind blanks so hard she might as well have given you that knock-out stuff again. You feel some part of you default, and proceed as if everything was going according to plan. You take a deep breath and brace yourself for your own idiocy.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “On behalf of the Earth--</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Come on, you almost said “earth of people”. Keep it together bitch, you can do this.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “I’m honored to make your...</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;SHIT! What was the word? It started with “A”. How the hell don’t you remember? What kind of an idiot are you? Fuck it, improvise!</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “...uh, honored to meet you. May our find knowledge and common...”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Oh Jesus Christ, you should quit before this gets any worse. Shit she&#039;s pretty. Just like you thought on the radio. That was already hard to deny, and now it’s getting hard to ignore. That isn’t fucking helping. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “You think I’m pretty?” she raises a stark black eyebrow, voice softening to hide what sounds like confusion and maybe a little relief, “I figured you probably didn&#039;t like me very much. I made a mistake. I hurt you. I tried to make it as easy as I could, but I know that couldn’t have counted for much. What I did was wrong. Please don’t hold this against us; we don’t mean humans any harm.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; She seems a little anxious. You don&#039;t have time to dwell on that though, because HOLY SHIT, you&#039;d said that OUT LOUD? You were even worse than you thought! At this rate you were going to doom your species to interstellar warfare. What did she mean SHE screwed up?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;For lack of a reply, she keeps talking. Her voice is a little hesitant at first, but it comes back to her.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “I just wanted to meet you,” she sighs, “We’ve known you were here all my life. I read about you in books. Saw you in movies. Nobody’s sure what to make of you, but me, I always thought there was probably someone down here worth knowing. That maybe there was more to you than it seemed at first. I wanted to prove that, or at least to know for sure...”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She slows, perhaps noticing herself rambling. She gauges your reaction with an empathetic but calculating eye. You can’t really pick one.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “...Certainly I didn’t mean to, uh, I guess, abduct you. That was wrong. I made a mistake. I should have run when you did, but I saw you fall, and I couldn’t just leave you. I’m sorry.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The cock of her ears and crease of her muzzle suggest what you think is ernesty. You’ve got to say something. Something on behalf of Earth. Part of you thinks this is a test of some kind. If so, you think you know the answer.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “I forgive you.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She relaxes visibly, her whiskers and eyebrows slack again.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Experiment’s still ruined.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Frustration replaces the anxiety on her tongue. To your surprise, her choice of words actually hurts a little.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Experiment?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Our meeting was supposed to be equitable. You weren’t supposed to be under duress. Now the data’s contaminated. It’ll just be another story; it won’t prove anything, and now someone might have seen...”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She falters on the last word, a subtle jolt of fear flashing down the crease of her muzzle.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “That’s the last thing I need.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You don’t FEEL contaminated. Your curiosity gets the better of you.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “What were you looking for?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She straightens her uniform, looking a little crestfallen.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “I&#039;m an anthropologist,” she admits, “Your kind was our First Contact. That was years ago, but we know very little about you, and we’ve never had a direct specimen. I’m the first to come here in a long time. Previous attempts were... unsuccessful. I thought I might have a decent theory as to why, but that banked on you not being under any duress, and acting of your own volition.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You can’t help feeling a little disappointed at not being the first actual contact, but you don’t miss the weight of the responsibility.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “What happened to the previous attempts?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Kal’Rashe flinches noticeably.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;“The first verbal exchange between our species occurred about nine months ago by way of one of your digital communication protocols. Your species’ first words to us, your Golden Record aside, were ‘Fuck off Moon Coons, we’re full. You can crash on Mars if you want.’ That’s what’s printed in our textbooks.” </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;That she says cheerfully, but she meets your gaze with resignation in her eyes. You almost keep yourself from pressing, but it’s no use.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “And First Contact?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The light in her eyes flickers out.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Suffice to say we didn’t get any data.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “What happened?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Her ears and whiskers wilt like cut lilies. She swallows, looking suddenly a lot more candid than before.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “We didn&#039;t get any data,” she repeats firmly. She inhales as if to continue, but instead just averts her eyes. Their surfaces shine glassily a moment before she blinks them clean again.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;From somewhere behind the cacophony of dissonant instincts raging in your head, one particularly warm-feeling one whispers its intentions.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Your first instinct had been that the information must be the ayy equivalent of classified, but this seems a little more personal. And that thing across from you might be extraterrestrial, but it kind of looks like it could use a hug.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It looks like it would be really NICE to hug too, like that crocodile plush you got on a trip to Florida when you were nine, and pretend you don&#039;t still sleep with.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But that would be a stupid risk, and you don&#039;t think you have the balls for that. Not even with Kennedy backing you up. Maybe just back off. That’ll have to do.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Sorry.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You retreat a step, making your apology as conspicuous as possible. She blinks again, and a little of the light returns.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “You were supposed to be different. You were going to board willingly, and I was going to interview you over dinner. We were finally going to have a real, proper Contact, and finally know more about each other than the speculations in our movies. We’d finally know if you really could be the friends we always used to think you would be. And my people&#039;s vessels would descend on your ports with goods and technology, and we&#039;d revel in your art in return. We&#039;d discover the universe together...”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Her gaze wanders into the distance. She shrugs wistfully.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Food’s cold now, and we may not have the luxury of time any longer. If someone saw..., well the last last thing we need is another setback.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Dinner, huh? That strikes you a little funny. Your hands are still shaking with traces of tepid adrenaline, but you don’t know that you feel what you’d call duress. Besides, there’s something disarming about the way she talks about the future. An idea floats up from the back of your mind, and you find yourself running with it.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “It wasn’t that bad, being &#039;abducted’, I guess,” you lie, “I think I can answer a few questions. Some of them would still be worth something, right?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Her face brightens.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “You’d do that? Humans may be a little braver than I thought.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Okay, that felt pretty good.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But something stops her, and the excitement drains from her face.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A particularly discordant chime from the flight deck.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Nivia appears again, concern frozen sharply in the blue haze of her face.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Kali?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Yesterday you hadn’t truly believed you’d ever hear a computer talk to you like it was a person. Now you were having a hell of a time accepting that the one in front of you sounded legitimately afraid.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Whatever was wrong, Kal’Rashe seems to already know. She glances over her shoulder to you as she turns again.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “There’s no time. Grab ahold of something.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You can’t tell if she’s afraid herself, but the sense of tranquility you’d managed to build up peels away like old wallpaper. As you feel the anxiety grab hold of you, so does a sense of disassociation.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’re dreaming.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You have to be.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But Kali throws herself into the captain’s chair, and you feel the vessel jolt and weave a little beneath you.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And your heart leaps firmly into your throat.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You stumble, catching yourself clumsily with a palm. Kali glances back again, this time from the chair.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Anon! Now!”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A shot of adrenaline oozes into your heart and makes the valves flutter. You scramble to your feet and throw yourself into the chair beside her, paying no mind to Nivia as you phase through her.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;That’s probably good, because the siren is louder now, and you’re being thrown into your seat so hard you should be listening to “Running in the 90’s”.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;All that time being so careful.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;That time you wouldn’t help Kim with a welding project because you thought the metal might be galvanized.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;That time you didn’t take an advil from the bottle with the label rubbed off.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The prom you didn’t go to.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;All the minor symptoms you’d looked up to make sure you didn’t have the plague.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And now you were going to die in the right seat of an alien spacecraft, without even the courtesy of knowing how or why.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The desert outside leaps into motion, and your eyes slide shut despite your best efforts.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But come on! If you’re going to die, you’re going to die awesome! Whatever’s happening, it’s your life, and you’ve got to face it!</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Not because they are easy...</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Not because they are easy...</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Not because they are easy...</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But because they are hard!</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Blackness greets you, and with it the overwhelming sensation that you had taken a step only for the Universe to decide there wasn’t one more stair after all.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Your arms fall to the rests of your office chair, and the mounting anxiety shatters and washes over you like a cold shower.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;As the basement slides back into focus, you find you’re laying cockeyed across the chair back, breath short and heart throbbing.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A dream.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A fuckmothering dream.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Or it almost certainly would have been if it weren’t for the hole in your jacket.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And perhaps the hiss and beep of the radio.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.-.--../-...-.--/-..----./-....--./--.-----/-...---./-...-.-./-..-.--./-..--.-./-...-.--/--.-...-/--.-----/-.-.--../-..--.-./-..--.-./-..-.-../--.-----/-..-.--./-..-...-/-..--..-/-..-..../-...--.-/-..-..-./-..----./-...-.--/-..-.--./-..-..../-..-...-/--.-...-/--.-----/-.--..-./-..-..../-..-...-/-..-.--./-...-.--/-..-..../-...--.-/--.-----/-..-.---/-..-..../-...-.-./-...--.-/--.-..../-..-.---/-..-..../-...-.-./-...--.-/--.-...-/--.-----/-.----../--.-----/-.-.-.-./--.-----/-.-.--../-.--..../-.--..../-.--...-/--.-...-</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Chapter 6, Mom, Look,  An Alien!</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It’s the 22nd now, a full week since the night in the woods.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And a full week since you or anyone has seen or heard anything from Kim.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;How much of that time you spent aboard the Triangle is difficult to say. Your best guesses suggest around twenty hours, assuming nothing fucky went on chronologically, and no time elapsed between the right seat and your chair in the basement.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Given the latter is a consideration at all, you don’t have very high hopes for the former.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Regardless, you’ve been back home five largely sleepless nights.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Your car is here, but there’s no trace of Kim.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;No one else seems to know either, though you haven’t done much asking around. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Nobody knows he rode with you that night. You might be worried, but you’re in no hurry to be some investigator’s number one person of interest either. Fortunately Kim’s parents are as absentee as they were wealthy.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And besides, Kali said to keep quiet. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’re not sure you trust her; in fact, the more time goes on the less you do. That said, as cuddly as she looked, you saw what she was capable of.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She’d saved you from a collapsed lung, and mended a broken bone or two in the space of an afternoon.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And you’d gotten to thinking she could probably kill you just as easily.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Whom or whatever she was, she probably wasn’t someone to be trifled with.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;So you’d done like she’d said.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’d checked the news, scanned the radio bands, and monitored 7000-7300 khz every hour on the hour.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;For better or worse, there hasn’t been much to hear. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A few NORAD call signs, but nothing you haven’t heard before.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Coast to Coast mentioned something about a UFO sighted near Las Vegas, which you would be virtually certain had been you and Kali if sightings like that weren’t so damn common.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Nothing on TV, nothing in the paper, and nothing from 7.0-7.3.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Anxiety has been burrowing in and out of you like worms in a buried corpse, gutting you until you can hardly eat let alone think.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Was it real? </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Who was she?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Where was Kim?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;What had happened?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;How did you get here?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’d tried sleeping it off, but that hadn’t afforded you anything more than nightmares.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Had Kim been around you could have set to trying to forget.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Could have told yourself it was all a dream somehow, at least if he’d have let you believe it.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But now things weren’t that simple.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;So far your parents had left you alone, figuring you’d gotten in a little trouble and maybe learned a thing or two about life and living.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But now they were starting to worry.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;They’d confronted you this morning, and you’d made a deal.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;That had gotten you here.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Back in your car, driving cautiously down Highway 2 with the afternoon sun dangling low in the pale, blue sky, and your mother sitting quietly in the passenger seat.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Every so often she looks over at you, eyes sick with worry.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You can almost see her skin crawl.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “You know sweetie, you can tell me what happened. It’ll be okay.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It’s the third time she’s said it, and you don’t blame her.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You wish you could answer, but what would you say?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The truth?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Well, that’s why you’d bargained for her instead of your father.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;He’d just tell you stories about all the drugs he did and trouble he got into as a kid, thinking he’d make you feel better.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Your mother though, she might hear the truth, or whatever you thought was the truth, and take it seriously. Especially hearing it from you.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She’d seen things she couldn’t explain.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Usually you dismissed them.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But this?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’re really not sure you can say.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’re not sure you even know how.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;So you sit in silence, tapping your finger on the steering wheel and listening to the crunch and slosh of snow and salt under the tires.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Could you at least tell me where we’re going?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It’s the second time she’s asked that one.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’ve got to give her something. You’re taking her there anyway.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And if you got the answers you were hoping to find there, she’d know the truth by the end of it. And believe it, too.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Whether you could trust her or not, if anyone knew where Kim was, it was Kali. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You haven’t heard from her, but you’ve woken more than once to what you could swear was a sonic boom. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It’s not a lot to go on, and you’d been back to Cuyahoga and come up empty handed, but there’s one other idea that’s been nagging you.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Magee Marsh.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A flash of relief crosses your mother’s face, but it’s gone as quickly as it came.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Can you tell me why?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You glance about nervously. The only thing watching you is a giant inflatable car dealership santa on the side of the road. The dying light casts long shadows across its face until the Big Man himself seems to leer at you as you pass. Doing your best to ignore him, you sift through the thoughts churning in the back of your mind until they gather in useful piles of words.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Kim and I saw something. We saw it there last Summer. We saw it again when we went out last week. I mean to see it today.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Honey, where is Kim?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “I don’t know.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Is that why we’re going?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Yes.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Silence falls, save for a bump from the tires as you cross the bridge over Oak Harbor and Lake Eerie spreads out in the passenger windows, looking cold, windswept, and desolate. Then the water’s gone again, and the miles tick by in a flurry of dead trees and stark, snowy fields.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The sun has about finished setting by the time you pull over into an empty hotel lot opposite the marsh entrance.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It’s not yet as dark as the night in Cuyahoga, and not so cold either, but when you cut the engine, a dense, milky silence settles on the place even thicker than the snow.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A profound desolation washes over you as the engine ticks the last of its heat away, and you find yourself hesitating on the door handle.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It seems almost as if pulling it would let in the icy vacuum of space itself, freeing it to freeze your skin and boil your blood and cast you adrift forever.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But you do open the door, and the sound of your boot in the snow shatters the silence. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Your mother follows, and by the light of your old metal flashlight you press up the park road together.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You can’t quite tell if you’re glad she’s there.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;This is your problem, not her’s. You’re not interested in making it her problem either. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’re eighteen, and a man now. And maybe Kali hadn’t hurt you, but god knew what really happened on that Triangle.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Or where the hell Kim had gone, and why.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;This was big. People could die.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;...maybe had died, though the idea makes you sick to your stomach.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Kim was your friend, and sometimes it seemed as if you could take on the world together.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Like you could really “blow the whole thing wide open”. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But Kim is gone, and in his place stands the woman who’d given you your life, and protected you from the monsters in your closet when you were four. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’re almost a head taller than she is now.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You know she’d die for you, but you also know it probably wouldn’t help.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And you know you sure as hell don’t want to lose her too.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But the darker it gets, the happier you are that you aren’t alone.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The trees here aren’t quite so tall as they were in Cuyahoga, but they grow tightly together and weave walls and roofs with their gnarled branches.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;In the Summer they’re full and beautiful, and shade a vibrant marsh that pulses with birds and frogs and dragonflies.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;In the evenings fireflies dodge and swarm like lighters at a rock concert, and at dusk the sky trades the birds for bats and softly-hooting owls.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’d smoked your first joint here, and one lucky evening you’d almost kissed your first girl.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But it isn’t Summer, and you’re not feeling very lucky today.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Where the marsh had been spreads only its bloated, icy corpse, lurking on either side of the narrow access road like the River Styx. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The knotted trees stand stark, bare, and skeletal, whiplike branches clawing at the sky as if frozen in a final bid to escape the ice.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Their final desperation seems to linger in the air, like that time you went to California and saw the tar pit fossils.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The cold sets in as you walk, and with it comes the nagging feeling that you’re being watched.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It’s just a tickle at first, like an insect on the back of your neck, but it builds.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It builds until you check your flanks like a nervous rabbit, making macabre shadow puppets of the trees as you sweep your flashlight beam across them.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;As much as you hate the feeling, the worst part is you can’t decide if it’s a good sign or not.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;By the second mile or so, you sling your leg over the parking lot gate and stumble onto the beach. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Lake Eerie greets you with a vicious breeze that sets the opening chords of The Wreck of the Edmund Fitzgerald playing in your head, and thick, tar-black waves that lick at your ankles like serpents’ tongues.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The darkness is is almost awe-inspiring, like how you imagine the space between stars.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’re alone in the Universe, adrift on your little island of pale, white light.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You might have forgotten you were walking at all if not for the soft crunch and sift of silt beneath your boots.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;A half mile or more the two of you trudge eastbound along the water’s edge, losing yourself in the lap and slosh of the waves and the gentle churning of sand underfoot.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Your breath is bated but steady; your mother’s slow and random.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She sighs sometimes, perhaps warding off unwelcome thoughts.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You distract yourself before your mind can start coming up with it’s own.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You’ve work to do.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It’s a longshot, but you don’t have anywhere else to turn.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;As nice as things seemed to be aboard whatever that thing was,</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;As kind as Kali had been to you,</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You can’t shake the feeling that something is very, very wrong.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It’s not just Kim, it’s bigger than Kim.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Bigger than either of you, like you’d said the night this had all started.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Maybe even bigger than Kal’Rashe herself.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You can’t let it be, and you can’t afford to screw up.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You play an old Apollo tape over and over in the back of your mind and try to convince yourself you’re cut of the same cloth that the crew were, or Houston, or even the goddamn janitors that shared the building with them.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And as you do, you practice.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.---.../--..-.../-.-..---/-.-.--.-/-.--.--./--......</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.-.--../--..-.-./-.--.-../-.-.--../-.----../--.-...-</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Again and again you tap the sequence on your thigh as you walk.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You tap it until you tap without thinking.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It’s not much. Maybe you’re just fooling yourself into not feeling helpless.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But it’s something, and by god it had led to a hell of a lot so far.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;G7XRI?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;S5KSC.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You almost don’t recognize the place in the winter. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Another tree’s fallen, and the rocks you and Kim had sat on that day are all but buried in snow.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But the two of you have been going back there for years now, and a lot of the landmarks of your teenage lives had transpired in that little clearing by the water. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;There was no way you could have missed it altogether. Certainly not after what you’d seen last Summer.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;So you brush the snow from your usual stump and sit back to study the sky awhile.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Most of it is as black as the water, but here and there the clouds part, and little colonies of stars gather in the cracks and voids.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Picking a particularly juicy cloud, you aim your flashlight skyward and edge the switch until it hangs between detents.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Ignoring a curious glance from your mother, you set to work.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.---.../--..-.../-.-..---/-.-.--.-/-.--.--./--......</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Snowflakes dance gaily in the beam as it flickers, twinkling when they catch the light. The clouds darken broodingly against the light.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.-.--../--..-.-./-.--.-../-.-.--../-.----../--.-...-</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You could almost swear you just saw something out of the corner of your eye, but surely that would be too easy.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Just a bat or something that caught the light.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Yeah, a bat.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You keep flickering.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.---.../--..-.../-.-..---/-.-.--.-/-.--.--./--......</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;G.7.X.R.I?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.-.--../--..-.-./-.--.-../-.-.--../-.----../--.-...-</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;S.5.K.S.C.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And again, and then a third time. Then you slip a memo pad from your pocket and get to work again. A minute’s practice and you start again from the top, adding to it this time.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.-.-.../-..-.---/-..----./-...-.--/--.-----/-..-.---/-..----./-...----/-...----/-..--.-./-..-...-/-..--.-./-..--.--/--......</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;What happened?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.-.-.../-..-.---/-..--.-./-...--.-/-..--.-./--.--.../-...--../--.-----/-.--.-../-..-.--./-..-..-./--......</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Where’s Kim?</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.-.----/-..-..--/-..--.-./-..----./-...--../-..--.-./--.-----/-.-.--.-/-..--.-./-...--../-...----/-..-..../-..-...-/-..--.--/--.-...-</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Please respond.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The darkness settles heavily when the flashing stops, the muscle memory for “please respond” still echoing in twitches of your thumb.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You meet your mother’s eyes again and find the confusion missing. You expect concern to replace it; some does, but with it comes a gleam of fascination.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “You were serious about the other night. You really saw something.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Her voice juggles guilt and curiosity. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Yeah.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “What did you see?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “A Black Triangle.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “And it wasn’t one of ours? You’re sure? I suppose if anyone would know, it would be you....”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Mom, I was on board.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Her eyes widen until the pupils shimmer in the starlight alone. Your heart skips a beat as you continue.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “I..., met one. I held her fucking hand! Felt her fur on my skin! I spoke with her--”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The weight of the situation comes crashing down around you.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;What happened had been real.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Suddenly you feel your mother’s hand on your shoulder, and realize you’ve been forgetting to breathe.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “Her fur? Honey, are you sure you didn’t dream this? I know you don’t have the easiest time with girls, and I know you have some... particular interests. Don’t you think maybe your subconscious could have been just, you know, indulging?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; “No.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;By all rights you should be petrified to find out she knew fuck all about that side of you, but you’re too busy flicking the flashlight switch.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Another cycle, and another, your hope wearing thin with the battery and the cold seeping into your jacket.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Both are dim by the top of the second hour, and the darkness around you wears on your nerves.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Another few cycles and you stand up again, leaving in the same silence that brought you here.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You relax a little when you finally reach your car, finding yourself surprisingly grateful for the warm, protective halo of a sodium street lamp that dangles overhead. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;But before you can open the door, something sends a shiver down your spine.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;That feeling again, like you’re being watched.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The light flicks off and plunges you into darkness.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And then back on.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Then off, and then back on again, faster this time.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Like any old lamp, really.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Only it hadn’t been blinking before.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Your mother is already in the car, but on a lark you note the flashes.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;-.-..--./-..-..../-...-.-./--.-----/-...-.../-..--.-./-...--.-/-..--.-./--.-----/-..--..-/-..-..../-..-..--/-..-..--/-..-..../-...-.../-.